<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Politics of the Multi-player<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.70)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6495'>Devon "Devonator" Clark</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6495&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 20, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> You&#39;re probably accustomed to single player LotR games--the mono a mono affairs.  It&#39;s probably second nature to you: bidding aggressively to go first in order to race to the end of the adventure path.  Or perhaps, you develop Shadow schemes designed expressly for decimating opposing fellowships and you use your Adventure Path to aid you.  In either case, you&#39;re winning the majority of your games.  Then, suddenly, you&#39;re invited to the big table--the true test.  The other giants of your local Lord of the Rings scene have pulled up their chairs, pooled their glass beads, and shuffled their decks in preparation for a massive free for all, an epic battle of your collective Middle-Earth wits.  You sit down to play a multi-player game.  You bid aggressive to go first, and you feel you have the advantage.  You double jump to site 3 and leave the rest of your competition in the dust.  You&#39;ve got it made.  Then, at site 5, you&#39;re suddenly swarmed by more Moria Scouts and Goblin Runners than you know what to do with…and they&#39;ve brought with them an Orthanc Assassin and Ulaire Nelya.  You use Power According to His Stature to dispense of the 1 vitality Goblin Runners, but you still have a host of Moria Scouts piled on Frodo to deal with.  Frodo gets overwhelmed.  You&#39;ve fallen victim to the greatest Multi-player mistake of all--playing a single-player style in a multi-player game.<br />
<br />
The truth is that multi-player games and single-player games are completely different experiences.  Yes, they share some similarities.  Your methods for winning are the same as in a single-player and many of the cards that you choose for your decks are the same, but the dynamics of gameplay and the styles that you must adopt are completely different from single-player to multi-player.  Single-player games are tests of muscle--of deck superiority.  Multi-player games are matches of wit, charm, and diplomacy.  The multi-player game requires a skill and a savvy that most trading card game devotees lack--personal skills.  In single player games, you must be the best deck-builder to win.  In multi-player games, you must be a studious and observant salesman to succeed.  You must keep off of your opponents&#39; collective radar, while preparing your coup with stealth and ingenuity.  In order to walk away the victor, you must bring to the table knowledge of the competitors, an awareness of the situation, and an ability to synergize.  If you can accomplish these 3 goals, you will put yourself in a position to win.<br />
<br />
KNOW YOUR OPPONENTS:<br />
<br />
You must know your competitors because they are your greatest assets.  They will be more valuable to you then the cards in your deck.  If a player poses a threat to you, you can use another player to eliminate that threat.  Knowing your competitors is essential to winning the multi.  True, you might not know them by name, but you don&#39;t need to.  You can recognize their personalities a mile away.  You&#39;ve played their type before, and you can predict their modus operandi as you sit down at the table.  Use this information to your advantage.<br />
<br />
The Incompetent:  Don&#39;t let the name fool you.  The incompetent is not stupid.  He just doesn&#39;t understand the game as well as you or I.  If you treat him like he is stupid, you may very well put yourself in a position to lose the multi-player game before it has scarcely begun . . . because the incompetent is a threat to one or two players (however, one of those two player is always himself).  The incompetent is the player who walks in every week talking about how broken What Are They is, and he&#39;s always the guy playing a multi exactly as if it were a single player.  He tries to pull ahead of the pack, and ultimately, that is his downfall.  He attacks one opponent with everything he has, but then laments when another more imposing fellowship waltzes by him due to his lack of minions.  He just doesn&#39;t understand.  He fails to see how multis and single-players are different.  After all, they&#39;re both LotR.  My advice to you is to leave this player to his illusions.  Often times, your treatment of these players will make the difference between victory and defeat.  Remember, these players are a potential threat to one player at the table.  Make sure that player is not you.  In fact, if you are savvy enough, you might even be able to define who that character is.  But whatever you do, don&#39;t cross the incompetent.  They have long memories, and they will come back to haunt you if you mistreat them.  Remember, they&#39;re not stupid.  How do you use the incompetents to your advantage?  When the incompetents are attacking one of your other adversaries, point out the things they miss, but do it in the form of a question.  &quot;Why didn&#39;t you use Wreathed in Shadow to reduce the archery total?&quot;  If you come out and tell them that they made a mistake, they will remember that specifically as they come after you.  Also, make off hand joking remarks about another player as he attacks the incompetent.  &quot;Whoa!  He&#39;s really got it in for you.&quot;  That will ensure that the Incompetent doesn&#39;t single you out.  Keep the incompetent on your side, and make him believe (through questions and subtle moves and decisions) that everything that this player does is his idea.  Then, when this player exhausts his resources, he&#39;ll burn himself out of the game.<br />
<br />
The Intimidator:  The intimidator is not a mean person.  He just has an intensely competitive nature and he wants you to recognize that he is one of the best players in the area.  Chances are he has an overabundance of raw machismo, so he succumbs to the &quot;I&#39;ll take you all at once&quot; syndrome, hence his affinity for the multi-player format.  This is the guy who walks in every week bragging about his killer deck and the killer combo he created.  He often comes across as arrogant, and he probably came by it with a measure of single-player success.  This player will make bold statements, though usually in jest, such as, &quot;Why do we even need to play the game, you know I&#39;m going to win.&quot;  This player may or may not understand the differences between single-player games and multi-player games.  Either way, the intimidator brings a mentality of &quot;me vs. the world&quot; to the table.  Chances are that he will not be the first to leave the table nor will he be the last.  This player is a dangerous adversary, because his means of attack is usually well refined.  Your best bet with the intimidator is to make him your ally.  Convince the intimidator to play his big guns the turn before your fellowship and odds are that he won&#39;t have the cards to do any significant damage to you.  Conspire with him to remove one player from the game and pool your resources.  Then, on your turn, he won&#39;t be able to put you out.  Plus, you&#39;ll have managed to anger another player by doing massive damage, and that player will turn his attention to the intimidator weakening him to a manageable level.  Typically, the intimidator&#39;s over-the-top play style and aggressive strategies betray him at one or two sites, and by site 7, this opponent is in serious trouble.  Keep the intimidator on your side, and then in his hour of need abandon him and pile some more minions on to overwhelm his ring-bearer.<br />
<br />
The Instigator:  The instigator is one of your two most dangerous opponents.  This player probably has no specific tells to let you know that he is the instigator as he sits down to the table; however his personality will be readily apparent as the game begins.  This is the player suggesting to everybody else that they find a way to remove that Under the Watching Eye.  This player understands the dynamics of the multi, and he tries to use those dynamics to his advantage.  He understands that he can&#39;t win on his own, and he will do his best to employ the assistance of every remaining player to further his ends, but he will do so in such a way as to make those players believe that it gives them a better chance to win.  So, the instigator will make suggestions to the table that the other players take action, but he will phrase it in such a way that it will be apparently in everybody&#39;s best interest.  Often times, this player will use varying degrees of subtlety in order to get each of the different types of players involved in his game plan.  This player is dangerous because all of his suggestions seem wise…however they are almost certainly wiser for him.  So, by convincing other players to act for the general good, he is really convincing the players to act for &quot;his&quot; good.  Meanwhile, his immediate goals are satisfied without his expenditure of resources.  The instigators are savvy and glib.  Your best bet is to reveal this player early in the game.  Reveal his schemes as what they are--self-serving and personally motivated.  Do this by launching an assault on this player.  He will respond by removing his veil of subtlety, and therefore any advantage he might have.<br />
<br />
The Invisible Player:  The invisible player is the other of the two most dangerous multi-player personae.  The invisible player&#39;s tell is that he has no tells.  He sits quietly at his corner of the table, eyes shifting from player to player, constantly counting his cards.  This player never makes a comment when an opponent plays a particularly frustrating card.  He&#39;ll simply rifle through the cards in his hand and look around the board.  He never betrays any concern or panic, because this player adheres to a particularly devious stratagem--out of sight is out of mind.  This player makes a deliberate attempt to fall off of the radar.  He surmises that if he can make you forget that he&#39;s playing (which is not as hard as you might think) than he will draw no attention and therefore no aggression.  Thus, this player reaches the end of the adventure path unscathed under the guise of anonymity.  He then uses that advantage to speed ahead or unleash that Shadow combination he has been slowly accumulating.  The invisible player is devious and crafty, because just as with the instigator, this player understands the dynamics of multi-player games, and that makes him dangerous.  He understands that he cannot succeed as one man against the world, so he allows the other players to pick each other apart before he takes action.  Therefore, the key to an invisible player&#39;s success is picking the right moment for action.  Timing is everything as an invisible player, and the same holds true for defeating them.  Make the player tip his hand early.  Target those unobtrusive silent types.  They&#39;re more dangerous than you realize.  <br />
<br />
The Entertainer:  The entertainer is a fun player to have at the multi-player table.  He plays the game for the fun of it, and he loves to laugh.  This player jokes from the moment he sits down to the moment he leaves.  He is a carefree spirit.  Chances are good that he understands the game but chooses not to take it seriously at all.  Often times, they will make moves just to see if they can pull it off.  And for that reason, this player is the most unpredictable, because he can either be a tangible threat or not.  Be prepared for anything.  The best way to handle the entertainer is to laugh at his jokes (genuinely, of course) and enjoy his presence, however don&#39;t let the entertainer&#39;s happy-go-lucky attitude throw you off guard.  This player wants to have fun, but they understand that fun is not an antonym of competitive.  This player likes to have his cake and eat it too.  Just remember, laugh and the whole world laughs with you.  Joke around with the entertainer.  If both of you are having fun, he&#39;ll probably let his aggression pass by you.  Then, seize your opportunity when it comes.  Be wary of the entertainers.  They are unpredictable.<br />
<br />
The Mentor:  The Mentor&#39;s are great people.  We like them a lot, because they tell us about what we can do to play better and make our decks better.  They think more of others than they do themselves.  However, in terms of the multi-player game, the mentor is his own worst enemy because he is liable to tell you what you can do to beat him.  These noble few are often the local tournament directors or store owners.  They have the means to be among the best players in the area, but they would rather make a positive gaming experience for others, so they sacrifice their victories in the name of encouragement.  Seeing other people enjoying themselves is what really drives the mentor, and for that reason, they are quick to forgive when you stab them in the back.  In fact, this type of player will laugh until the last of their twilight tokens is in their bag.  In truth, there&#39;s a little bit of mentor in all of us, but I&#39;m talking about the people who are 50% mentor or more.  These people are great guys, but they are their own worst enemy.  Expect these people to leave the table early, although occasionally, they will win a game.<br />
<br />
The Newby:  Finally, we come to the new player.  Having played in CCGs for a while, you know how to recognize the new players from the experienced players, so I&#39;m not going to comment on their tells.  We all know them.  The truth is that they&#39;ve come to the game because they enjoyed the movie and have thus found a hobby.  Nobody at the table takes them seriously.  The intimidator might try and scare them into submission, however if there is a mentor or a strong instigator at the table, these players can marshal the new player&#39;s courage and turn him into a short-term force of destruction.  In your quest for victory, the newby can be an invaluable weapon.  By using them to put somebody out of the game, you&#39;ll increase their enjoyment for their success, and it will bring you one step closer to your victory.  Of course, don&#39;t worry about this player stealing victory.  He doesn&#39;t know the game well enough to be able to win, but with your help, he can know the game well enough to defeat one of your opponents.<br />
<br />
There you have it.  These are your opponents.  Know them!  Learn their tendencies.  Learn the tactics that tend to work against them.  Know who to build alliances with and know which of those alliances will endure.  Create synergy with other compatible personalities, and try to become invisible or an instigator.  Of course, there are no absolutes.  Nobody is 100% Intimidator or 100% Newby.  Therefore, your best bet is to be both instigator and invisible.  But remember, what I have given you is a template for various caricatures and nothing more.  People are much more complicated.  The multi-player game is all about reading people and using what you read there to your ultimate advantage.  These templates can be invaluable to your success, but they are not the complete solution.   You must also have a situational awareness, patience, and timing to succeed, but if you can use your knowledge of personalities along with patience and timing to create a positive synergy, you will put yourself in the best position for winning the multi-player games.<br />
<br />
SITUATIONAL AWARENESS<br />
<br />
As I have said, the single-player games are drastically different than the multi-player games.  In the single-player game, during each of your shadow phases, you play as many minions and shadow cards as your twilight pool allows.  However, the same does not necessarily hold true for multi-player games.  In the multi, you must understand that you go through too many shadow phases to play shadow cards during every one.  Instead, you must recognize when it is best to play shadow cards.  You must have a situational awareness.  If you have that situational awareness, your sense of timing and patience will follow naturally.  Situational awareness is one of the 3 fundamental characteristics of a successful multi-player game player.  You must know when it is best to play and hold your cards.  Adding a minion just because you can is not always a good idea.  Of course, it&#39;s not necessarily a bad idea either.  If you only want to play the minion for some token resistance, it&#39;s not a good idea.  However, if you want to get cards out of your hand so you can get to other cards in your deck, it can be a good idea.  Or it can be a good idea to eat up twilight.  You can use this as a tool to give direction to your opponents.  By playing or not playing minions, you can cause your opponents to direct their minions where you want them to go.  For example, let&#39;s assume that the current fellowship is not very strong, but the next fellowship is very strong.  The player whose shadow phase immediately follows yours seems to be chomping at the bit to play some nasty minions.  You know he&#39;s playing Moria and he declares that he needs 8 twilight to do what he wants to.  You can infer from this that he has a Cave Troll with hammer, and he wants to use it right away.  He doesn&#39;t recognize that it would be better saved a turn for that subsequent strong fellowship.  You can make that decision for him.  If there is 10 twilight in the pool, use 3 of it for some token resistance forcing that Cave Troll to wait a turn, thereby not wasting a strong minion like the Cave Troll on a weak fellowship.  Yes, at times, it is a good idea to force an opponent to hold a big gun one turn longer, because in so doing, you can have a measure of control on how your opponents focus their attack on other players.  It is for this reason that I say that your opponents are more valuable to you in a multi-player game than your own deck.  Use them to your advantage.  <br />
<br />
Now, I also mentioned that there are times when it is best not to play cards.  One example of such a case is against the fellowship directly preceding yours.  Often times, it will be in your best interest not to play any cards against the player directly preceding you because it will force your other opponents to use their shadow against him, leaving them with depleted shadow on your turn.  Of course, this is not always the case.  That is why I say that you must have a strong situational awareness.  There are too many variables to speak or think in absolutes.  Often, it&#39;s a gamble, but if you read your opponents and ask questions, you can get a strong feel for what the best course of action is.<br />
<br />
Ask questions, but follow the rules.  According to the rules, you can collaborate with the other shadow players, but you can&#39;t directly say what you have in your hand.  For this reason, I find it is best to collaborate using the language of twilight and wounds.  Find out how many wounds your opponent could possibly inflict and how much twilight they need to do it.  This will give you a strong measure of which players have the strong shadow hands, and this sets the parameters for the situation.  Asking questions and gathering all of the information that you can regarding opposing shadow hands will define your situational awareness and increase your odds of success.  For example, let me return to the situation of diluting opposing shadows directly before your fellowship phase.  During the fellowship directly before yours, you ask who can do a lot of damage and who needs how much twilight.  One opponent states that he can do many wounds for little twilight.  You, in turn, suggest that he does his damage now and potentially remove a player from the table.  Your opponent drops his big nasties right before your turn, paving the way for an easier fellowship for you.  Meanwhile, despite the fact that it was your idea, the recipient of the beating will remember the aggressor instead of the instigator . . . and note, I said instigator.  This is a very instigator-esque ploy, and hence, you can see how instigators can be so dangerous.  The advice of doing massive damage to an opponent to remove him from the table seems wise . . . but it is most certainly wiser for the instigator.  The instigator has used his situational awareness to his ultimate advantage.  As a matter of fact, situational awareness is the defining characteristic of the instigator.<br />
<br />
SYNERGY<br />
<br />
The final fundamental asset of the multi-player environment is synergy--the extent to which your deck or strategy works in accordance with other decks or strategies.  To put it simply, if you play in a 6-player game in which 3 players are playing the Sauron culture, those three Sauron decks will achieve an immediate synergy and immediately be stronger.  Imagine if each of these decks were playing 4 Orc Bowmen.  It&#39;s conceivable that you could have 12 Orc Bowmen on the table.  Then, if one of these players plays one Sauron Orc, the opposing fellowship must take 12 wounds.  These decks work together, and for that reason, it is in their best interests to keep each other alive until the other fellowships are dead.  So, they might not play their minions against the other Sauron players&#39; respective fellowships to increase their collective ability to make it to the late game.  That&#39;s deck synergy.  <br />
<br />
If you&#39;re playing in a multi-player game, it is best for you to utilize strategies that work in conjunction with other shadow strategies.  Moria decks, due to their twilight adding minions and seemingly never ending supply of minions always achieve some measure of synergy with other Shadow decks.  Nazgul and Sauron often achieve synergy, because one is burden dependent and the other adds burdens.  Or they might not achieve synergy if the Sauron culture goes the Orc Bowmen, Hate, Under the Watching Eye route.  That wouldn&#39;t help the Nazgul shadow.  Whatever the cultures, your best bet is to play strategies that will work with all other cultures.  For example, the Isengard culture might play Spies of Saruman.  Killing the fellowship&#39;s archery is always beneficial to the other shadow players.  The Nazgul might play Wreathed in Shadow for the same reason.  Moria&#39;s swarming and twilight adding strategy is a great synergistic tool for all shadow cultures, hence They Are Coming and Goblin Armories are musts.  As for Sauron, Desperate Defense of the Ring and Thin & Stretched both create limited synergy because many cards in opposing cultures are burden-dependent.  You can also achieve interpersonal synergy.  People&#39;s personalities or strategies can often work well together.  For example, the invisible player has an automatic synergy with the intimidator, because the invisible player&#39;s goal of not being noticed fits directly into the goal of the intimidator--to be noticed and feared immediately.  However, in this situation, the intimidator&#39;s goal is not in synergy with the invisible player, because the invisible player&#39;s strategy does not aid the intimidator&#39;s strategy.  As you can see, synergy is not necessarily a two way street.  Therefore, it is up to you to try and create it.  Treat the multi-player table like a kindergarten sandbox.  You must play well with others.  Achieve some kind of synergy, and you will drastically increase your chances of winning.<br />
<br />
SUMMARY<br />
<br />
In conclusion, remember your 3 fundamental multi-player game assets.  Be aware of your opponents.  Know their personalities and what it will take to beat them.  Be aware of the situation.  Use your shadow cards to dictate how that situation can be used to your advantage.  Be aware of your level of synergy.  If you can fit your strategy into another player&#39;s shadow strategy, you will immediately increase your ability to win.  You will be the one player to rule them all!<br />
<br />
Thanks for reading my article!  I look forward to seeing you at the big table, soon...<br />
<br />
Devon &quot;That is unless you&#39;re invisible!&quot; Clark <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3327&view=1&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
